While Paper 1 (Fourier-Net) uses frequency-domain representations for efficiency, it does so in a fixed, static manner for image registration—not adaptive compression—and lacks any notion of dynamic architecture or feedback-driven refinement. Paper 2 (ATP-Net) employs temporal pyramids and attention but is focused on scene classification, not compression or funnel-shaped networks. Paper 3 (AD-ESN) touches on adaptive network structures for graph dynamics, which loosely relates to architectural plasticity, but it operates in a completely different domain (graph time series) and lacks spectral awareness. Paper 4 explores richer neuron dynamics in SNNs for ASR, which is orthogonal to architectural shaping. Paper 5 introduces sample-specific encoder perturbations in frozen models, conceptually related to dynamic behavior but not structural adaptation during encoding.

Idea 0 (FAF-SAA) proposes a strong, spectrally-aligned static funnel with speculative refinement—novel, but still within the realm of learned attention and auxiliary decoding seen in some generative models (e.g., SpecDec). In contrast, DSMN introduces **real-time, input-driven morphing of the funnel shape via a differentiable control loop**, which represents a more radical departure from standard autoencoder design. The integration of control theory concepts (SSC as a feedback controller), dynamic channel reallocation via Concrete relaxation, and LDV in latent spectral token space constitutes a new paradigm in *adaptive neural compression architectures*. This level of runtime plasticity in response to spectral flux—especially in non-stationary signals—is not addressed in any of the provided papers or commonly in the compression literature.

